# Environment Configuration Structure
#
# This project uses a modular environment configuration system:
#
# File naming convention:
#   .env.{variant}            - Base config for a build variant
#   .env.{variant}.{platform} - Platform-specific overrides
#
# Build variants:
#   - debug    : Local development
#   - staging  : Staging/testing environment
#   - release  : Production environment
#
# Platforms:
#   - android  : Android-specific overrides
#   - ios      : iOS-specific overrides
#   - js       : Web/JavaScript-specific overrides
#   - jvm      : JVM/Server-specific overrides
#
# Examples:
#   .env.debug              : Base debug config (all platforms)
#   .env.debug.android      : Android debug overrides (e.g., use 10.0.2.2 for localhost)
#   .env.release            : Base production config
#   .env.release.ios        : iOS production overrides
#
# How it works:
#   1. Base variant config is loaded first (.env.{variant})
#   2. Platform-specific overrides are applied if they exist (.env.{variant}.{platform})
#   3. Gradle task generates expect/actual Kotlin code
#   4. Each platform automatically gets its specific config at compile time
#
# To switch build variants:
#   ./gradlew generateEnvConfig -PbuildVariant=staging
#   ./gradlew generateEnvConfig -PbuildVariant=release
#
# Default variant is 'debug'

# Example variables:
BASE_URL=http://localhost:8080
# API_KEY=your_api_key
# FEATURE_FLAG_X=true

